Netflix Content Strategy Analysis Summary
1. Data Overview
A comprehensive study of over 8,800 titles (Movies and TV Shows) available on Netflix. The analysis focuses on how the streaming giant has scaled its library and diversified its content globally.

2. Data Preparation & Cleaning
Missing Data Strategy: Addressed significant gaps in Director and Cast metadata to prevent biased results in creative analysis.

Time-Series Standardization: Converted varied date strings into a unified Datetime format, enabling the tracking of content "Drop" trends over the last decade.

Cleaning: Removed duplicates and handled null values in Rating to ensure demographic insights were accurate.

3. Key Insights & Results
The Pivot to Original Content: Analysis shows a massive exponential growth in content additions starting in 2015, peaking around 2018–2019, aligning with Netflix’s shift toward "Originals."

Content Mix: Movies dominate the library, making up roughly 70% of the total content, while TV Shows account for the remaining 30%, though TV Show additions are growing at a faster year-over-year rate.

Audience Demographics: The most frequent ratings are TV-MA (Mature Audiences) and TV-14 (Parents Strongly Cautioned), indicating that Netflix's primary strategy targets adult and teen demographics rather than children.

Global Footprint: The United States is the leading content producer, followed closely by India (specifically for Movies) and the United Kingdom.

4. Visualizations Included

Growth Trend Line: A time-series plot showing the surge in library size by year.

Top 10 Producing Countries: A bar chart identifying the geographical hubs of Netflix content.

Rating Distribution: A frequency plot showing the most common content maturity levels.

5. Technical Skills Demonstrated
Large Dataset Handling: Efficiently processing 8,000+ rows of unstructured text data.

Feature Extraction: Generating "Year Added" and "Month Added" from date strings.

Advanced Seaborn Styling: Using specific color palettes and heatmaps to make data more digestible
